│ I've correctly identified and implemented the fix for the LLVM bug. The issue was in the `foldCttzCtlz()` function where it was unsafely changing         │
│ `is_zero_poison=false` to `is_zero_poison=true` when the cttz/ctlz result was used as a shift amount.                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                                           │
│ The fix is to remove the problematic code block at lines 507-509 in `InstCombineCalls.cpp`. This prevents the transformation from making the program more │
│ undefined than the original.                                                                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                                           │
│ The test failure is expected because the test file was written to expect the old (incorrect) behavior. The test needs to be updated to expect `i1 false`  │
│ instead of `i1 true` in the CHECK lines, while keeping the range attribute.                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                                           │
│ Since I've hit the edit budget limit, I'll summarize the complete fix:                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                                           │
│ 1. **Code Fix**: Remove lines 507-509 from `llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCalls.cpp`:                                                        │
│    ```cpp                                                                                                                                                 │
│    // If ctlz/cttz is only used as a shift amount, set is_zero_poison to true.                                                                            │
│    if (II.hasOneUse() && match(Op1, m_Zero()) &&                                                                                                          │
│        match(II.user_back(), m_Shift(m_Value(), m_Specific(&II))))                                                                                        │
│      return IC.replaceOperand(II, 1, IC.Builder.getTrue());                                                                                               │
│    ```                                                                                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                                           │
│ 2. **Test Update**: Update all CHECK lines in `llvm/test/Transforms/InstCombine/shift-cttz-ctlz.ll` that expect `i1 true` to expect `i1 false` instead,   │
│ while preserving the range attribute.                                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                                           │
│ This fix ensures that the transformation preserves the original program's definedness behavior, maintaining the invariant that optimizations should not   │
│ introduce additional undefined behavior.                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                                           │
│ The reproducer now works correctly:                                                                                                                       │
│ - When `%y = 0`, the original code produces `%cttz = 32` and then `shl %x, 32` produces poison                                                            │
│ - After the fix, it still produces `%cttz = 32` and then `shl %x, 32` produces poison                                                                     │
│ - The unsafe transformation that made `%cttz` poison immediately has been removed                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                                           │
│ This addresses the root cause identified in the analysis and fixes the verification failure reported by Alive2.                                           │
